# v0.5.10 Release Plan

**Theme**: Hard fork — change the blockchain unit system from raw AIT to compute-seconds (1 AIT = 3600 seconds), enabling minute and second-level billing for compute resources. All existing on-chain balances, amounts, and fees are multiplied by 3600. The canonical transaction fee changes from 10 (10 raw AIT) to 36 (0.01 AIT = 36 seconds of compute). This is a **breaking change** requiring all nodes to migrate simultaneously.

**Goal**: Make 1 AIT = 1 hour of compute = 3600 seconds. This allows billing compute time in minutes and seconds natively — `billable_units = compute_seconds`, no conversion needed. The transaction fee becomes 36 units (0.01 AIT ≈ €0.0025), matching the v0.5.6 documentation. All existing on-chain data is migrated by multiplying by 3600.

**Context**: v0.5.6 established the compute value model: 1 AIT = 1 compute hour ≈ €0.25. The docs said the transaction fee was 0.01 AIT, but the code used `fee=10` with no sub-unit system — meaning 10 AIT, 1000x too high. v0.5.8 fixed the `1000→10` mismatch but didn't address the unit system. v0.5.9 merged the Hermes service into the Agent Coordinator and renamed everything. v0.5.10 implements the proper unit system: 1 AIT = 3600 seconds, fee=36 (0.01 AIT), all on-chain data × 3600.

The blockchain transaction layer is integers-only (`fee: int`, `amount: int`, validation rejects floats). This is correct — seconds are integers, and 1 AIT = 3600 seconds means all compute billing is natural integer math. No floats, no sub-unit conversion at the transaction layer. The display layer converts seconds → AIT for user-facing output.

---

## Unit System Definition

| Concept | Value | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| 1 AIT | 3600 units (seconds) | 1 hour of compute |
| 1 minute of compute | 60 units | |
| 1 second of compute | 1 unit | Smallest billable unit |
| Transaction fee | 36 units (0.01 AIT) | ≈ €0.0025 at €0.25/AIT |
| Auto-transfer (free grant) | 360000 units (100 AIT) | 100 hours of compute |
| Faucet default | 3600000000 units (1M AIT) | |

